1 e.d. Provides a student may contact the student's parent or authorized caregiver
2 during the school day if needed by using a school telephone made available to
3 the student in a manner and location designated by the school.
4 3. Notwithstanding subsection 2, a school may not prohibit a student from possessing or
5 using a personal electronic communication device, if:
6 a. A medical provider licensed under title 43 determines the possession or use of a
7 personal electronic communication device is necessary for the health or well-
8 being of the student; or
9 b. The possession or use of a personal electronic communication device is required
10 by the student's individual education program under the:
11 (1) The Individuals with Disabilities Education Act [Pub. L. 91-230; 84 Stat. 121;
12 20 U.S.C. 1400 et seq.], a plan under section;
13 (2) Section 504 of the federal Rehabilitation Act of 1973 [29 U.S.C. 794], or
14 other; or
15 (3) A plan that must be accommodateddeveloped in accordance with state or
16 federal law requiring accommodation.
17 4. A school district shall collect data annually with the goal of measuring the impact of its
18 policy on student behavior, mental health, disciplinary incidents, school attendance,
19 and academic performance. By July 1, 2026, the superintendent of public instruction
20 shall establish a uniform system to enable a school district to report all data as
21 required under this section.
22 5. Upon the adoption and implementation of a policy in accordance with this section, a
23 school district shall:
24 a. Ensure the policy is communicated to students, parents, and authorized
25 caregivers; and
26 b. Publish the policy in student and personnel handbooks.
